docs.abstract: “The Eyes of Texas,” once sung at minstrel shows, plays at football games and other sports events at the University of Texas at Austin.
docs.snippet: “The Eyes of Texas,” once sung at minstrel shows, plays at football games and other sports events at the University of Texas at Austin.
docs.lead_paragraph: For generations, students at the University of Texas at Austin have stood up at sports games, raised their right hand to form the symbol of the storied Texas Longhorns and belted out “The Eyes of Texas,” a campus anthem.

headline.main: Texas Football Players Call on University to Drop a Song Steeped in Racist History
headline.print_headline: Texas Athletes Want Song With Racist Roots Dropped

docs.lead_paragraph: After more than a decade of litigation over James Brown’s estate, which he, the Godfather of Soul, had largely bequeathed to underprivileged students in South Carolina and Georgia, the chief justice of South Carolina’s Supreme Court seemed irritated.

docs.lead_paragraph: Archivists in Washington, D.C., made a timely discovery this week: the original handwritten Union Army record of an order that brought emancipation to enslaved people in Texas at the end of the Civil War.

docs.abstract: When the history of the Trump presidency is written, the clash with protesters that preceded President Trump’s walk across Lafayette Square may be remembered as one of its defining moments.
docs.snippet: When the history of the Trump presidency is written, the clash with protesters that preceded President Trump’s walk across Lafayette Square may be remembered as one of its defining moments.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After a weekend of protests that led all the way to his own front yard and forced him to briefly retreat to a bunker beneath the White House, President Trump arrived in the Oval Office on Monday agitated over the television images, annoyed that anyone would think he was hiding and eager for action.

headline.main: How Trump’s Idea for a Photo Op Led to Havoc in a Park

docs.abstract: These shows may fill in some of the gaps left by your school curriculum and deepen your understanding of what’s happening now.
docs.snippet: These shows may fill in some of the gaps left by your school curriculum and deepen your understanding of what’s happening now.
docs.lead_paragraph: Even with half of the year left, it’s already clear 2020 will be one for the history books. A deadly pandemic, economic collapse, and a reckoning on race and police brutality will ensure that this year will be remembered as one of seismic change. And in times of uncertainty and upheaval, one of the best ways to understand the future is to look to the past.

headline.print_headline: Listening to the Past Is Kind of Perfect

docs.abstract: The coronavirus has led to the collapse of New York’s usual admissions system, and protests against racism have highlighted entrenched division.
docs.snippet: The coronavirus has led to the collapse of New York’s usual admissions system, and protests against racism have highlighted entrenched division.
docs.lead_paragraph: When New York City became the national epicenter of the coronavirus pandemic, its once-sacrosanct practice of sorting thousands of children into selective public schools suddenly collapsed: The metrics that dictate admissions evaporated as schools shuttered.

headline.main: A School Admissions Process That Caused Segregation Fell Apart in Weeks
headline.print_headline: As an Admissions System Fell Apart, Many Said: It’s About Time
